Run the following code chunk to import the data. In this chunk, I am removing NAs.

After going back over it after finishing the hw, I came up with this, which I think maybe answers the question. I am not sure, Im going to leave all of this rambling in and also just ask in class :)

table <- sharks %>% 
  group_by(county, injury) %>% 
  summarize(n=n()) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = county,
              values_from = n,)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'county'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
table

San Diego has the highest number of incidents.

  1. Use the table from #5 to make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by county.
table %>% 
  pivot_longer(-injury,
               names_to = "county",
               values_to = "n_incidents") %>% 
  group_by(county) %>% 
  summarize(n_incidents=sum(n_incidents, na.rm=T)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=county, y=n_incidents))+
  geom_col()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title="Number of Incidents by County",
       x="County",
       y=NULL)

  1. Are all incidents involving Great Whites fatal? Make a plot that shows the number and types of incidents for Great Whites only.
